<subsection xml:id="subsec-surface-area-of-prisms" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Surface Area of Prisms</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.7 Surface Area
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
        </introduction>
        <ul>
            <li>Determine the surface area of prisms, pyramids, cones, frustums and spheres</li>
            <li>Explore the use of the surface area and volume of solids in real-life situations</li>
        </ul>
    </objectives>

    <p>
        A <term>prism</term> is a three-dimensional solid made of two identical faces called <term>faces</term>, and connected by rectangular faces. Triangular prisms, cylinders, and cuboids are examples of prisms. The surface area of a prism can be found by calculating the area of each face and adding them to the area of the faces.
    </p>

    <activity>
        <statement>
            <p>
                <term>Work in groups:</term> Form groups of <m>2</m> or <m>3</m> students.
            </p>
            <p>
                <term>Materials Needed:</term>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Pen or pencil
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Grid/graph paper or plain paper
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Rulers
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Pre-made nets of triangular prisms (optional)
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            <p>
                <term>Instructions:</term>
            </p>

            <sidebyside widths="45% 45%" valign="middle">
                <image>
                    <latex-image label="triangular-prism-solid">
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1, every node/.style={scale=0.8}]
                            % prism vertices
                            \coordinate (A) at (0,0,0);
                            \coordinate (B) at (3,0,0);
                            \coordinate (C) at (1.5,4,0); % Increased height for 10cm scale
                            \coordinate (D) at (0,0,4);
                            \coordinate (E) at (3,0,4);
                            \coordinate (F) at (1.5,4,4);

                            % faces (Rear)
                            \draw[-] (A)--(B)--(C)--cycle;
                            
                            % Connecting edges
                            \draw (A)--(D) node[midway, left, sloped] {9 cm};
                            \draw (B)--(E);
                            \draw (C)--(F);
                            
                            % Front face
                            \draw[thick] (D)--(E)--(F)--cycle;

                            % Measurements on the front triangular face
                            % face label
                            \draw[-] (0,-0.3,4) -- (3,-0.3,4) node[midway, below] {8 cm};
                            % Height dashed line
                            \draw[dashed] (1.5,0,4) -- (1.5,4,4) node[midway, right] {10 cm};
                            % Right angle marker
                            \draw (1.5,0.2,4) -- (1.7,0.2,4) -- (1.7,0,4);
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>

                <image>
                    <latex-image label="triangular-prism-net">
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.6, every node/.style={scale=0.8}]
                            % Main rectangular body
                            \draw (0,0) rectangle (8,4);
                            % Triangular flaps
                            \draw (0,4) -- (4,7) -- (8,4);
                            \draw (0,0) -- (4,-3) -- (8,0);

                            % Labels
                            \node[left] at (0,2) {Length ($l$)};
                            \node[below] at (4,0) {Base ($b$)};
                            \draw[dashed] (4,4) -- (4,7) node[midway, right] {Height ($h$)};
                            
                            % Optional: width of the side rectangles
                            % \node[above] at (2,4.5) {side}; 
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </sidebyside>
            <p>
                <ol marker="a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            In your group, draw a triangular prism and its net on paper.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Label the dimensions of the triangular face and the length of the prism.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Calculate the area of the triangular face.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Calculate the perimeter of the triangular face.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Multiplying the perimeter of the face by the length of the prism to get the lateral area.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Add the areas of the two triangular faces and the lateral area.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            <p>
                A triangular prism has two identical triangular faces and three rectangular faces.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>
    <insight>
        <p>
            A <m>\textbf{prism}</m> is a geometric object with two identical, parallel faces and straight sides connecting them. These include rectangular prisms, triangular prisms, and pentagonal prisms (which is shown)
        </p>
        <p>
            <image>
                <latex-image label="pentagonal-prism">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=3]
                        % Back pentagon
                        \coordinate (A) at (0,1);
                        \coordinate (B) at (0.95,0.31);
                        \coordinate (C) at (0.59,-0.81);
                        \coordinate (D) at (-0.59,-0.81);
                        \coordinate (E) at (-0.95,0.31);
                        \fill[gray!20] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- (D) -- (E) -- cycle;
                        \draw[thick] (A)--(B)--(C)--(D)--(E)--cycle;
                        % Front pentagon (shifted)
                        \coordinate (A1) at (2,0.2);
                        \coordinate (B1) at (2.95,-0.49);
                        \coordinate (C1) at (2.59,-1.81);
                        \coordinate (D1) at (1.41,-1.81);
                        \coordinate (E1) at (1.05,-0.49);
                        % Side faces (light blue, fairly opaque)
                        \fill[blue!30,opacity=0.9] (A) -- (B) -- (B1) -- (A1) -- cycle;
                        \fill[blue!30,opacity=0.9] (B) -- (C) -- (C1) -- (B1) -- cycle;
                        \fill[blue!30,opacity=0.9] (C) -- (D) -- (D1) -- (C1) -- cycle;
                        \fill[blue!30,opacity=0.9] (D) -- (E) -- (E1) -- (D1) -- cycle;
                        \fill[blue!30,opacity=0.9] (E) -- (A) -- (A1) -- (E1) -- cycle;
                        \fill[gray!10] (A1) -- (B1) -- (C1) -- (D1) -- (E1) -- cycle;
                        \draw[thick] (A1)--(B1)--(C1)--(D1)--(E1)--cycle;
                        % Connecting edges
                        \draw (A)-- node[midway, above right] {Length $l$} (A1) (D)--(D1) (E)--(E1);
                        \draw[dashed] (B)--(B1) (C)--(C1);
                        \draw[dashed] (A)--(B)--(C)--(D);
                        % Labels
                        \node at (2.00,-0.96) {Face $F$};
                        \node[below] at ($(C1)!0.5!(D1)$) {Perimeter $P$};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
        </p>
        <p>
            To calculate the surface area of a prisms, we use the formula:
            <md>
                <mrow> \text{Surface Area} \amp = 2\times \text{Area of Face} + \text{Perimeter of Face} \times \text{Length} </mrow>
                <mrow> \amp = 2F + Pl </mrow>
            </md>
            where <m>F</m> is the area of the face, <m>P</m> is the perimeter of the face, and <m>l</m> is length of the prism.
        </p>
        <p>
            This works for any prism, including rectangular prisms (see <xref ref="subsec-surface-area-of-cubes-and-cuboids"/>), triangular prisms, and cylinders (see <xref ref="subsec-surface-area-of-cylinders"/>)
        </p>
        <p>
            In the special case of a <term>triangular prisms</term>, we have <m>F = \frac{1}{2} \times b \times h</m> where <m>b</m> is the base of the triangle and <m>h</m> is the height of the triangle. The perimeter <m>P</m> is the sum of the three sides of the triangle.
        </p>
        
    </insight>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Find the surface area of a triangular prism with face <m>8 \, \text{cm}</m>, triangle height <m>3 \, \text{cm}</m>, and length <m>12 \, \text{cm}</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <sidebyside widths="40% 50%">
            <image width="50%">
                <shortdescription>Triangular Prism example</shortdescription>
            <latex-image label="surface-area-triangular-prism-example">
                \begin{tikzpicture}  
                    % Define points
                    \coordinate (A) at (0,0,0);
                    \coordinate (B) at (3,0,0);
                    \coordinate (C) at (1.5,2,0);
                    \coordinate (D) at (0,0,3);
                    \coordinate (E) at (3,0,3);
                    \coordinate (F) at (1.5,2,3);

                    % Draw the face (now at the bottom) with shading
                    \fill[gray!30] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- cycle;

                    % Draw the face edges
                    \draw[thin] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- cycle;

                    % Draw vertical edges
                    \draw[thin] (A) -- (D);
                    \draw[thin] (B) -- (E);
                    \draw[thin] (C) -- (F);

                    % Draw top face
                    \draw[thin] (D) -- (E) -- (F) -- cycle;

                    % Draw hidden lines
                    \draw[dashed] (D) -- (F);
                    \draw[dashed] (D) -- (E);
                    \draw[dashed] (E) -- (F);
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
            </image>
        
                <image width="50%"> 
                <shortdescription> Net of a triangular prism example.</shortdescription>
                <latex-image label="surface-area-triangular-prism-net-example">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        % Define face rectangle
                        \draw[thick,dashed] (0,0) rectangle (8,8);

                        % Triangular faces
                        \draw[very thick] (0,0) -- (4,-4) -- (8,0);
                        \draw[very thick] (0,8) -- (4,12) -- (8,8);
                        \fill[gray!50] (0,8) -- (4,12) -- (8,8);

                        % Fold lines (dashed)
                        \draw[thick,dashed] (4,12) -- (4,8);
                        \draw[thick,dashed] (4,-4) -- (4,0);
                        \draw[very thick] (8,0) --(12,0) --(12,8) --(8,8);
                        \draw[very thick] (0,0) --(-4,0) --(-4,8) --(0,8);
                        
                        % Labels
                        \node[above] at (4,10) {\huge 3 cm};
                        \node[below] at (4,-2) {\huge 3 cm};
                        \node[above] at (4,0.5) {\huge 8 cm};
                        \node[right] at (8,4) {\huge 12 cm};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
            </sidebyside>
            <p>
                The area of one triangular face is:
                <me>
                    \text{Area of triangle} = \frac{1}{2} \times 8 \times 3 = 12 \, \text{ cm}^2
                </me>
                <me>
                    \text{Two faces} = 2 \times 12 = 24 \, \text{ cm}^2
                </me>
                <me>
                    \text{Perimeter} = 8 + 3 + 3 = 14 \, \text{ cm}
                </me>
                <me>
                    \text{Lateral area} = 14 \times 12 = 168 \, \text{ cm}^2
                </me>
                <me>
                    \text{Total S.A} = 24 + 168
                </me>
                <me>
                    = 192 \, \text{ cm}^2
                </me>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                An octagonal prism has an octagonal face with area <m>96 \, \text{cm}^2</m> and perimeter <m>32 \, \text{cm}</m>. The length of the prism is <m>12 \, \text{cm}</m>. Calculate the total surface area.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Surface area of a prism is given by <m>2F + Pl</m>, where <m>F</m> is face area, <m>P</m> is perimeter of the face and <m>l</m> is the length.
            </p>
            <p>
                Given: <m>F = 96 \, \text{cm}^2</m>, <m>P = 32 \, \text{cm}</m>, <m>l = 12 \, \text{cm}</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                Lateral area = <m>P\times l = 32 \times 12 = 384 \, \text{cm}^2</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                Two faces = <m>2F = 2 \times 96 = 192 \, \text{cm}^2</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                Total surface area = <m>192 + 384 = 576 \, \text{cm}^2</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
            Find the Surface area of the triangular prism with a slant height of <m>5 \, \text{cm}</m>, height of the triangular prism <m>12 \, \text{cm}</m> and a face of <m>8 \, \text{cm}</m>. 
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
            Step 1: Find the area of the face.
            </p>
            <p>
                The triangular face has a slant height of <m>5 \, \text{cm}</m> and face <m>8 \, \text{cm}</m>. Using pythagorean relationship height is:
                <md>
                    <mrow> = \amp \sqrt{(5\,\text{cm})^2 - (4\, \text{cm})^2}</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp \sqrt{25 \, \text{cm} -16\, \text{cm}} = 3\, \text{cm}</mrow>
                    <mrow> \text{area of a triangle} = \amp \frac{1}{2}\times b \times h</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp \frac{1}{2} \times  8 \, \text{cm} \times 3 \, \text{cm} </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 12  \,\text{cm}^2</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
            Step 2: Add the area of the face with the lateral area.
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{Surface Area} = \amp  \text{area of face} + \text{lateral area}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\text{Lateral area} = \amp \text{Perimeter of Face} \times \text{Length}</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp (8 + 3 + 3) \, \text{cm} \times 12 \, \text{cm}</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 14 \, \text{cm} \times 12 \, \text{cm}</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 168\, \text{cm}^2</mrow>
                    <mrow>\text{Total Surface Area} = \amp 24\, \text{cm}^2 + 168\, \text{cm}^2</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 192\, \text{cm}^2</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                The surface area of the triangular prism is <m>192 \, \text{cm}^2</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

        <exercise  label="ex-finding-the-surface-area-of-a-composite-solid">
        <stack label="stk-finding-the-surface-area-of-a-composite-solid" source="stack/top/2-0-Measurement-Geometry/2-7-Surface-Area-and-Volume-of-Solids/2-7-5-Surface-Area-of-a-Triangular-Prism/Finding-the-Surface-Area-of-a-Composite-Solid.xml" />
    </exercise>

    <exercise  label="ex-finding-the-surface-area-of-a-triangular-prism">
        <stack label="stk-finding-the-surface-area-of-a-triangular-prism" source="stack/top/2-0-Measurement-Geometry/2-7-Surface-Area-and-Volume-of-Solids/2-7-5-Surface-Area-of-a-Triangular-Prism/Finding-the-Surface-Area-of-a-Triangular-Prism.xml" />
    </exercise>

    <exercise  label="ex-finding-the-surface-area-of-a-triangular-prism-tent-problem">
        <stack label="stk-finding-the-surface-area-of-a-triangular-prism-tent-problem" source="stack/top/2-0-Measurement-Geometry/2-7-Surface-Area-and-Volume-of-Solids/2-7-5-Surface-Area-of-a-Triangular-Prism/Finding-the-Surface-Area-of-a-Triangular-Prism-(Tent-Problem).xml" />
    </exercise>
    <exercises xml:id="exercises-triangular-prism-surface-area">
        <!-- Level 1: Simple formula applications -->
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A rectangular box measures <m>12 \text{cm}</m> by <m>7 \text{cm}</m> by <m>5 \text{cm}</m>. Calculate its total surface area.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    Total surface area of a rectangular box: <me>\text{SA} = 2(lw + lh + wh)</me>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Substituting <m>l=12\,\text{cm},\; w=7\,\text{cm},\; h=5\,\text{cm}</m> gives:
                    <me>\text{SA} = 2(12\times7 + 12\times5 + 7\times5) = 2(84 + 60 + 35) = 2(179) = 358 \, \text{cm}^2</me>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A company is designing a cube-shaped promotional stand with a side length of <m>5</m> meters. The stand will be covered with high-quality wallpaper on all six faces. If one roll of wallpaper covers <m>10</m> square meters, determine the number of rolls required to fully cover the cube.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A cube-shaped metal box has side <m>1.5 \text{m}</m>. If metal sheets cost <m>Ksh. 2,000</m> per <m>\text{m}^2</m>, calculate the total cost of making the box.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    A cube with side <m>s = 1.5\,\text{m}</m> has surface area <me>\text{SA} = 6s^2 = 6\times(1.5)^2 = 6\times2.25 = 13.5 \, \text{m}^2</me>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Cost at <m>2000\,\text{Ksh/m}^2</m> is <me>13.5 \times 2000 = 27{,}000 \, \text{Ksh}</me>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A small storage room is designed with an edge length of <m>4</m> meters each side. The floor, four walls, and ceiling all need to be tiled. If each tile covers an area of <m>0.5</m> square meters, determine the total number of tiles required to fully cover the interior of the room.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    For a room with edge length <m>s = 4\,\text{m}</m>, the total interior area to tile (floor + ceiling + four walls) is the total surface area of a cube: <me>\text{SA} = 6s^2 = 6\times4^2 = 6\times16 = 96 \, \text{m}^2</me>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Each tile covers <m>0.5\,\text{m}^2</m>, so number of tiles required is <me>\dfrac{96}{0.5} = 192</me> tiles.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <!-- Level 2: Direct prism formula uses -->
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A pentagonal prism has a pentagonal face with area <m>54 \, \text{cm}^2</m> and perimeter <m>30 \, \text{cm}</m>. The length of the prism is <m>10 \, \text{cm}</m>. Find the total surface area.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    Surface Area = 2F + Pl. Given <m>F = 54 \, \text{cm}^2</m>, <m>P = 30 \, \text{cm}</m>, <m>l = 10 \, \text{cm}</m>:
                </p>
                <p>
                    Lateral area: <me>Pl = 30 \times 10 = 300 \, \text{cm}^2</me>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Two faces: <me>2F = 2 \times 54 = 108 \, \text{cm}^2</me>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Total surface area: <me>2F + Pl = 108 + 300 = 408 \, \text{cm}^2</me>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A regular hexagonal prism has a hexagonal face with side <m>6 \, \text{cm}</m>. The length of the prism is <m>10 \, \text{cm}</m>.
                </p>
                <image>
                    <latex-image label="hexagonal-prism-diagram">
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.0, every node/.style={scale=0.9}]
                            % Draw back hexagon (shifted)
                            \coordinate (A) at (0:1);
                            \foreach \i in {0,60,...,300} { \coordinate (B\i) at ({cos(\i)*1},{sin(\i)*1}); }
                            % front hexagon shifted right
                            \begin{scope}[xshift=3cm, yshift=-1cm]
                                \foreach \i in {0,60,...,300} { \coordinate (C\i) at ({cos(\i)*1},{sin(\i)*1}); }
                            \end{scope}
                            % draw hexagons
                            \draw[thick,fill=gray!10] (C0) -- (C60) -- (C120) -- (C180) -- (C240) -- (C300) -- cycle;
                            \draw[thick] (B0) -- (B60) -- (B120) -- (B180) -- (B240) -- (B300) -- cycle;
                            % connect corresponding vertices
                            \foreach \i/\j in {0/0,60/60,120/120,180/180,240/240,300/300} { \draw (B\i) -- (C\j); }
                            % labels
                            \node[above right] at ($(C60)!0.5!(B60)$) {$10$ cm};
                            \node[below] at ($(C240)!0.5!(C300)$) {$6$ cm};
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
                <p>
                    Work out:
                </p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The area of one hexagonal face.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The total surface area of the prism.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            A regular hexagon can be split into six equilateral triangles of side <m>s</m>. The area of one equilateral triangle is <m>\frac{\sqrt{3}}{4}s^2</m>, so the area of the hexagon is
                            <me>
                                A = 6 \times \frac{\sqrt{3}}{4}s^2 = \frac{3\sqrt{3}}{2}s^2.
                            </me>
                            With <m>s = 6 \, \text{cm}</m> we get
                            <me>
                                A = \frac{3\sqrt{3}}{2} \times 6^2 = \frac{3\sqrt{3}}{2} \times 36 = 54\sqrt{3} \, \text{cm}^2 \approx 93.53 \, \text{cm}^2.
                            </me>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p> Perimeter of the hexagon is <m>P = 6s = 36 \, \text{cm}</m>. Lateral area = <m>P \times l = 36 \times 10 = 360 \, \text{cm}^2</m>.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Two faces = <m>2A = 2 \times 54\sqrt{3} = 108\sqrt{3} \, \text{cm}^2 \approx 187.06 \, \text{cm}^2</m>.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Total surface area = <m>2A + Pl = 108\sqrt{3} + 360 \approx 547.06 \, \text{cm}^2</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <!-- Level 3: Triangular prism standard applications -->
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A triangular prism has a triangular face of face <m>10 \, \text{cm}</m> and height <m>6 \, \text{cm}</m>. The two equal sides of the triangle are <m>8 \, \text{cm}</m> each. The length of the prism is <m>15 \, \text{cm}</m>. Find its total surface area.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    Surface Area = 2F + Pl. Interpreting the statement as base <m>b=10\,\text{cm}</m>, triangle height <m>h=6\,\text{cm}</m>, equal sides <m>8\,\text{cm}</m> and prism length <m>l=15\,\text{cm}</m>:
                </p>
                <p>
                    Area of triangular face: <m>F = \tfrac{1}{2}bh = \tfrac{1}{2}\times 10 \times 6 = 30 \, \text{cm}^2</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Perimeter: <m>P = 10 + 8 + 8 = 26 \, \text{cm}</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Lateral area: <m>Pl = 26 \times 15 = 390 \, \text{cm}^2</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Total surface area: <m>2F + Pl = 2\times 30 + 390 = 60 + 390 = 450 \, \text{cm}^2</m>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A triangular prism has a triangular face of base <m>10 \text{cm}</m> and height <m>6 \text{cm}</m>. The two equal sides of the triangle are <m>8 \text{cm}</m> each. The length of the prism is <m>15 \text{cm}</m>. Find its total surface area.
                </p >
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    Interpreting the triangular face as base <m>b=10\,\text{cm}</m> and triangle height <m>h=6\,\text{cm}</m> with equal sides <m>8\,\text{cm}</m> and prism length <m>l=15\,\text{cm}</m>:
                </p>
                <p>
                    Area of triangular face: <me>F = \tfrac{1}{2}bh = \tfrac{1}{2}\times10\times6 = 30 \, \text{cm}^2</me>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Perimeter: <me>P = 10 + 8 + 8 = 26 \, \text{cm}</me>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Lateral area: <me>Pl = 26 \times 15 = 390 \, \text{cm}^2</me>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Total surface area: <me>2F + Pl = 2\times30 + 390 = 60 + 390 = 450 \, \text{cm}^2</me>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A triangular tent is shaped like a triangular prism. The triangular cross-section has base <m>4 \text{m}</m> and height <m>3 \text{m}</m>. The slant sides are <m>5 \text{m}</m> each. The length of the tent is <m>6 \text{m}</m>. Find the total surface area of the tent canvas (including the two triangular ends).
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    Area of triangular cross-section: <me>F = \tfrac{1}{2} \times 4 \times 3 = 6 \, \text{m}^2</me>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Perimeter of triangular cross-section: <me>P = 4 + 5 + 5 = 14 \, \text{m}</me>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Lateral area: <me>Pl = 14 \times 6 = 84 \, \text{m}^2</me>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Total surface area: <me>2F + Pl = 2\times6 + 84 = 12 + 84 = 96 \, \text{m}^2</me>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <!-- Level 4: Multi-step / Heron -->
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    If a litre of paint covers an area of <m>2 \, \text{m}^2</m>, how much paint does a painter need to cover:
                    <ol marker="a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                A rectangular swimming pool with dimensions <m>4 \, \text{m}</m> by <m>3 \, \text{m}</m> by <m>5 \, \text{m}</m> (the inside walls and floor only)
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                the inside walls and floor of a circular reservoir with diameter <m>7 \, \text{m}</m> and height <m>5 \, \text{m}</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    Surface Area = 2F + Pl (use appropriate surface area formulas for each shape). Substituting the given values gives:
                </p>
                <p>
                    a) <m>47 \, \text{litres}</m>
                    b) <m>77 \, \text{litres}</m>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    The total surface area of a triangular prism is measured as <m>360 \, \text{cm}^2</m> and its height is 20 cm. If the triangular face has sides measuring <m>9 \, \text{cm}</m>, <m>12 \, \text{cm}</m>, and <m>15 \, \text{cm}</m>, verify that this value is correct by calculating the surface area from the given dimensions.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    Surface Area = 2F + Pl. Substituting the given values and showing working:
                </p>
                <p>
                    Semi-perimeter: <me>s = \frac{9 + 12 + 15}{2} = 18 \, \text{cm}</me>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Area of triangular face (Heron):
                    <me>F = \sqrt{s(s-9)(s-12)(s-15)} = \sqrt{18\times9\times6\times3} = \sqrt{2916} = 54 \, \text{cm}^2</me>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Perimeter: <me>P = 9 + 12 + 15 = 36 \, \text{cm}</me>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Lateral area: <me>Pl = 36 \times 20 = 720 \, \text{cm}^2</me>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Total surface area: <me>2F + Pl = 2\times54 + 720 = 108 + 720 = 828 \, \text{cm}^2</me>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A bridge support structure has the shape of a triangular prism, with a face measuring <m>10 \, \text{cm}</m>, <m>17 \, \text{cm}</m>, and <m>21 \, \text{cm}</m>, and a height of <m>50 \, \text{cm}</m>. Paint needs to be applied to coat its entire surface. Compute the total surface area, which will be painted.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    Surface Area = 2F + Pl. Compute using Heron's formula for the triangular face with sides 10 cm, 17 cm and 21 cm, and prism length <m>l=50\,\text{cm}</m>:
                </p>
                <p>
                    Semi-perimeter: <me>s = \frac{10 + 17 + 21}{2} = 24 \, \text{cm}</me>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Area of triangular face: <me>F = \sqrt{s(s-10)(s-17)(s-21)} = \sqrt{24\times14\times7\times3} = \sqrt{7056} = 84 \, \text{cm}^2</me>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Perimeter: <me>P = 10 + 17 + 21 = 48 \, \text{cm}</me>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Lateral area: <me>Pl = 48 \times 50 = 2400 \, \text{cm}^2</me>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Total surface area: <me>2F + Pl = 2\times84 + 2400 = 168 + 2400 = 2568 \, \text{cm}^2</me>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <!-- Level 5: Ambiguous or missing-parameter exercises (leave last) -->
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A glass showcase is designed in the shape of a triangular prism, with a triangular face of <m>5 \, \text{cm}</m>, a height of <m>12 \, \text{cm}</m>, and a prism length of <m>20 \, \text{cm}</m>. If all faces are to be made of glass, calculate the total glass area required.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    Surface Area = 2F + Pl. The statement gives a "triangular face of 5 cm" and triangle height 12 cm and prism length 20 cm, but it is ambiguous whether "5 cm" is the area of the triangular face or a side length (base).
                </p>
                <p>
                    If <m>F = 5 \, \text{cm}^2</m> (face area) and <m>l = 20 \, \text{cm}</m>, the perimeter <m>P</m> is not provided so the lateral area cannot be determined and the total surface area cannot be computed.
                </p>
                <p>
                    If instead the statement meant base <m>b=5\,\text{cm}</m> and triangle height <m>h=12\,\text{cm}</m>, then
                    <me>F = \tfrac{1}{2}bh = \tfrac{1}{2}\times5\times12 = 30\,\text{cm}^2</me>
                    and <m>P = 5 +  ? + ?</m> (other side lengths needed) so <m>Pl</m> still cannot be determined without the remaining side lengths.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Please provide the perimeter of the triangular face or all three side lengths so the total surface area can be computed.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A prism is constructed with a triangular face of face <m>8 \, \text{cm}</m> and height <m>12 \, \text{cm}</m>. Determine the area of the triangular face, then use the given dimensions to compute the total surface area.
                </p>
                <image source="triangular-prism.png" width="50%">
                    <shortdescription>${0:}</shortdescription>
                </image>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    The area of the triangular face can be computed from base <m>b=8\,\text{cm}</m> and triangle height <m>h=12\,\text{cm}</m> as <m>F=\tfrac{1}{2}bh = \tfrac{1}{2}\times 8 \times 12 = 48\,\text{cm}^2</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    The perimeter <m>P</m> of the triangular face and the prism length <m>l</m> are not both given, so the lateral area <m>Pl</m> cannot be determined from the data provided; therefore the total surface area cannot be computed without <m>P</m> and <m>l</m>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>
</subsection>